# Understanding the Set Interface
Q1. What Exactly Is a Set?
Standard Definition
    In Java, the Set interface is a type of collection that doesn’t allow duplicate values.
    It’s part of Java’s Collections Framework and is used when you only want unique entries.

Simple Explanation
    Think of a Set like a guest list where each name can appear only once. Even if someone
    tries to register multiple times, their name will only be added once. It’s like the
    system quietly says, “You’re already here!”

Q2. Why Is Set So Useful?
    Let’s be honest — in most real-life apps, we don’t want repeated data.
        1. You don’t want two users with the same username.
        2. You don’t want two students with the same roll number.
        3. You don’t want the same tag added multiple times to a blog post.

    Manually checking for duplicates in every list is messy and time-consuming. That’s where
    Set saves the day. It does all of that checking for you, automatically.

# Key Points to remember:
    1. No Duplicates: A Set ensures that each element is unique, making sure there are no redundant items.
    2. Unordered Collection: The order of elements is not guaranteed, like a collection of tech gadgets thrown into a drawer.
    3. Use Cases: Perfect for managing collections like user IDs, unique email addresses, or any scenario where repetition is a no-go.

# Common Interview Questions and answers:

    Q1. What is a Set in Java?
    Answer: A Set is a type of collection in Java that doesn’t allow duplicate values.
            If you try to add the same item more than once, Java will ignore it.
            This makes Set perfect when you only want unique items in your data.

    Q2. How is a Set different from a List?
    Answer: 1. A List allows duplicates and stores items by position (like index 0, 1, 2...).
            2. A Set does not allow duplicates and doesn’t store items by position.
               You can’t get the “first” item — it just stores things without order.

    Q3. What happens if I add the same item twice to a Set?
    Answer: The second time you add the same item, nothing happens. Java simply
            ignores the duplicate. No error is shown, and the Set stays the same.

    Q4. What are some real-life examples of when to use a Set?
    Answer: 1. Storing usernames (no two users can have the same name)
            2. Collecting student IDs (each student should have a unique number)
            3. Managing email subscriptions (to avoid sending duplicate emails)
            4. Listing tags or labels in a blog or app (one tag per topic)

    Q5. Can I access elements in a Set by index?
    Answer: No, you can’t. Unlike lists, a Set doesn’t have positions. You can check
            if something exists in the Set or loop through all items, but
            you can’t get something like set.get(0) — that won’t work.